{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a constrained 2D packing problem where rectangles must contain specific points and approximate target areas without overlapping. I have decomposed this into a spatial partitioning/ordering problem and a geometric optimization problem.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "spatial_ordering_and_partitioning",
      "instructions": "Develop an algorithm to determine the optimal sequence and spatial boundaries for the rectangles. Given the 10000x10000 grid and $N$ points $(x_i, y_i)$ with target areas $A_i$, implement a recursive quadtree-style decomposition or a sweep-line partitioning strategy. The goal is to divide the 10000x10000 space into $N$ non-overlapping rectangular cells $C_i$ such that each $C_i$ contains its respective point $(x_i, y_i)$. Use a priority queue to process points based on their target area $A_i$ (e.g., largest area first) to ensure high-value advertisers are allocated space before the grid becomes too fragmented."
    },
    {
      "label": "rectangle_geometry_optimization",
      "instructions": "For each assigned cell $C_i$ (defined by $[x_{min}, x_{max}] \times [y_{min}, y_{max}]$) and its target area $A_i$, calculate the dimensions of the final rectangle $R_i$. The rectangle $R_i$ must satisfy: 1) $R_i \subseteq C_i$, 2) $(x_i, y_i) \in R_i$, and 3) $\text{Area}(R_i) \approx A_i$. Implement a logic that maximizes $\text{Area}(R_i)$ up to $A_i$ by expanding from $(x_i, y_i)$ towards the boundaries of $C_i$. Specifically, solve for width $w$ and height $h$ such that $w \cdot h = \min(A_i, \text{Area}(C_i))$, while ensuring $x_i - w/2 \ge x_{min}$, $x_i + w/2 \le x_{max}$, etc. If a perfect aspect ratio is impossible, use a greedy expansion that prioritizes the dimension with the most remaining slack."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "Combine the partitioned cell boundaries from Helper 1 with the optimized rectangle dimensions from Helper 2. The final output must be a list of rectangles defined by $(x1, y1, x2, y2)$ for each advertiser, ensuring no two rectangles overlap and all points are contained."
}
```

